Observation Details: Continuing immature with some variation on its location.  Was not in on its snag above the lake  near the bandstand but at 515p flew out of the thick stand of eucs at the east end, where it was fairly well-concealed, and flushed everything on the lake as it did a pass across and back.  Disappeared back into this area for approx 30 minutes before flying onto the perch near the bandstand where it was spotted by sharp-eyed Elena. Showing some white base on dark nape feathers, as well as mottled white on chin, breast and on back in flight.  Tail also showing speckled white in center of feathers, framed by dark feathers.  Eyes not pale but showing an amber tone when the light hit it. Ultimately flew back into hiding higher up in the eucs on the east end of the lake.

Observation Details: The eagle was flying with a duck in its talons when first observed.  The eagle landed on an old piling in the Albany mudflat and ate the duck there (see photos). There are few Bald Eagle records at the Albany Bulb, but this is a little surprising to me, given the availability of prey species during the winter months.

Dramatic interaction between BAEA and COME. In initial scan of lake I noticed a bird that, unaided by magnification, appeared to be some sort of goose hybrid. In fact, it was a BAEA lying prostrate on the water with wings flattened on the surface like pontoons. After a few seconds remaining relatively motionless, the eagle began to propel itself forward and lift off from the water. Clutched in its talons was a male COME. It was able to lift the bird almost completely out of the water before falling back to the surface with the merganser still underneath. After several more attempts to take off, the eagle lost its grip and made repeated tries to recapture the merganser. The COME was able to successfully dive and evade until the eagle departed to the shoreline and the merganser swam away toward its flock. Photos show attempts of eagle to recapture merganser.
Not as regular as the Red-shouldered Hawk, but a periodic visitor nonetheless.

Observation Details: saw 1 adult (possibly 2) & 1 immature eagle  //  An adult Bald Eagle was flying circles over the bluff when I began birding the beach.  Later, an immature Baldie made several passes over the bluff while I was on the trail to-from Peregrine Pt. I saw it on three separate occasions.  From Peregrine Pt, I scoped an adult Bald Eagle in a tree on the opposite side of the lake (i.e., across lake to S, not simply across the narrow cove by Peregrine Pt).  I first thought this was a different adult, since it is not that uncommon to find two adults here together.  However, we have entered the nesting/baby-raising time, so I may have missed the first adult looping back to the far side of the water.

Observation Details: At approximately 8 AM an adult flew to the nest from the north. Judging by its deep gape and large head it appears to be the female. When I first saw the nest it showed no evidence of any occupants. However as soon as the adult landed on a branch next to the nest two eaglets pop their heads up. They did not beg for food. The adult remained roosting to the right of the nest. At 8:48 AM one adult flew over the nest from south. Then the female flew to occupy the usual roost in the large tree at the corner of 208 and Pines to the east. I’m continuing to watch the Nest but there has been no activity. they did not vocalize which seemed unusual. I found the female roosting in the usual spot and obtain photos. I returned to the nest and once again did not catch sight of the eaglets. I failed to get any photos of the eaglets although I did see both at once. The female disgorged a pellet which I photographed.

I watched one adult grab a small stick from the top of a nearby tree then took it to the nest.  Why???  Then they were both in the nest then one of them departed. Based on timing and actions of the birds, I assume they have little white fluff balls in the nest even though I can't see them.

Observation Details: It was a clear, cold and very sunny day and noontime  I was walking in my yard and first noticed the bald eagle flying from the east above the treeline near the Leary Conservation property. Actually just short of the record # of Bald Eagle observed by our team at this site. Eagles were omnipresent today throughout the entire survey period, and from our high vantage point, were often able to observe almost all birds at once, especially given our circumferential field of view. We carefully looked at each additional bird observed, noted direction off flight if not perched, and other plumage characteristics, and considered numerous observations as simply repeat occurrences of an earlier observation. At this site, eagles tend to perch around the upper rim of the active landfill in somewhat dispersed fashion, facilitating individual counting.

Continuing bird.  When we arrived at the golf course, we spotted the eagle circling over the first two side by side ponds.  It flew out towards middle road, before circling back around. We followed it to number 17 pond, where it landed high up in a Norfolk pine tree. It sat there for about 5 minutes before flying low across the pond, trying to catch mallards.  It then flew across the course and landed on one of the large poles, and sat up there for at least ten minutes (Note: Tropicbird remains were found beneath these poles earlier today).   After watching it for a bit, it flew back across to 17, where it landed back in the same pine tree.  After that it chased a few ducks in the air, and then flew back over towards the first two ponds.  The crows spotted it and chased it back towards Morgan's Point.  Overall the eagle stayed on the course for about an hour, and had also been seen earlier that day.  The course was closed to golfers, so the eagle was likely taking advantage of this.

Same juvenile bird from yesterday. We waited at the old ferry dock for about fifteen minutes before we spotted the eagle flying in along the coast. It flew low right over us, before crossing over the water towards Morgan’s point. The crows started to harass it as usual, flying over from Morgan’s towards it. It didn’t seem bothered by them at all, flying over the the coastline of Morgan’s, where it skimmed the water ad snagged a fish with its talons. Then flew up into one of the casuarinas where we located it again using a scope. It ate for about 20 or more minutes before eventually hopping up onto a higher branch where it was in full view. We were joined by David and a few others who also saw it at this point. After a while it flew up into some higher casuarinas to then right of the dead tree it was in yesterday. The crows returned and started mobbing it again, at one point at least five if them were sitting in the tree surrounding it. It was still in the same tree when we all left.

I was driving west on Hwy 532 from Stanwood to Camano, and as I came up to the Stillaguamish bridge I saw this Bald Eagle in the distance, over about Davis Slough. I casually kept watching it and the road and traffic. It actually flew right towards me and landed on a large metal cylinder at Eide Road.  As I glanced at the bird it began lifting up a very large prey item and dismembering it. That was just too good to pass up so I pulled over to the shoulder, put on my Emergency Lights, and grabbed my camera from the passenger seat.  To me, what remains of the animal, impresses me as about the size of a Mallard duck. The eagle was occasionally flitting a feather here and there (see 2nd photo) - so not a fish or bunny.

Media notes: Feeding on spawned salmon.
Observation Details: Eagles of all ages are congregating around the salmon run on the South Thompson River. The river banks are strewn with spawned fish. Hundreds of eagles are at the River now, but this spot has an exceptionally high density. The eagles may be attracted to this site for the clumps of mature cottonwood, which they like to perch on. Cottonwoods are more extensive along the banks here than most of the river, as much of the River's edge has been cleared of trees. Also this stretch of River has large areas of exposed gravel bars, many mid-stream, which the eagles use when they feed.

At approx. 1000 one adult and the juvenile departed heading south where the fourth flew to leaving one adult.  I have noticed on average that once these birds catch a fish the next time they fly is between 30 min (if real hungry) and one hour 20 min.  Typically it is around an hour between each fishing expedition.

Observation Details: Continuing presence of mature and immature eagles at Big Pool Lake and surrounding area. One adult eagle perched for awhile in a high tree near the western end of the lake. Three immature eagles flew in from the direction of the Potomac River to the eastern end of the lake and continued west.  At the end of my visit, I saw one adult in the company of an immature eagle fly out of the forested interior of the state park, pass over the parking area near the C&O Canal bridge, and continue on in the direction of the lake. The eagles have been reported previously by multiple observers.   At one point, the three immature eagles that flew in together circled each other playfully in the air, calling as they did.  One distinctive eagle, with a mostly white head and abundant white on the body, made a failed attempt at fishing in the lake. [It has a rather ghostly appearance in gray light, therefore I call it the "phantom" for reference in my notes.]  Two brown-headed immature eagles came in close to me, circling directly above, as if studying me, before flying off to a distant part of the lake. This has occurred on each of my last three visits where I saw eagles.

Locality: Paris Landing State Park, Buchanan US-TN 36.43777, -88.07832
Observation Details: One adult Bald Eagle was banded with a silver band - left leg. The juvenile Bald Eagle appears to be injured and unable to fly away. It tried to fly off "Pelican Island" (the sand bar where the Snowy Owl was earlier this month) but was unable to do so. I took a series of shots of it flapping it's wings and lifting off only up a few feet and for a few seconds. (It did not have prey in its talons.)  It ended up in the middle of a flock of American White Pelicans. They scattered when the eagle was lunging forward but then they would come back and observe it. The photos are distant and over exposed. I plan to go back tomorrow to see if it is still stuck there. I stopped at the bridge and took some shots from there so that I could inspect its physical appearance more closely but could not see anything obviously wrong. The juvenile eagle is very young - lots of white throughout and in the last shot from the bridge the bill looks black. Time observed = 40 minutes.

One nesting. Male was eating in the nest with the nesting when I arrived, then flew to a ater level perch and periodically drank for 30 minutes, hen  to an adjacent tree for two hours, where it napped, off and on. It then began vocalizing excitedly and flew out of sight into the cove to the southwest. The nesting flapped it's wings and hovered over the nest three times, for up to ten seconds each time, before softly landing back in the nest. When the adult male left, the nestling settled down into the nest. At 6:45pm, the fledgling, flying very close to the water surface, flew out of the southwest cove and landed in a lakeside tree on the west bank, about 300 yards southwest of the nest. The adult male, which was following the fledgling, perched in a tree in the middle of the lake, near the fledgling's location, and vocalized. They were at these locations when I left. No female.

One Bald Eagle on the nest (I think it is the female), then that (female) adult sat on a branch above the nest calling to the mate. You can see (her) looking to her right, which is where I believe her mate was. Even thoughI couldn't see her mate,  think she knew right where he was. One of the other photos shows the (female) Bald Eagle with her beak open making her loud call to the mate, I assume because she wants food. It seemed clear that the male could hear her calls because the other adult (I assume the male) did a fly by “check in,” with the vocalizing (female) adult who was still sitting on the branch watching him do the "fly by check in" The (female) Eagle on the branch,  had just been sitting on the nest with the eggs. The flying (male) adult had no food to deliver, he just came close to the female adult, to check in and let her know he was working on it, and then flew back to the lake to hunt some more. At least I assume that was what was being communicated between the two eagles based on their body postures and vocalizations. In the one photo of the (female) Eagle looking down, she is looking directly at the eggs inside the nest. To me that is why she didn't leave to get her own food. The crow activity around here is fierce, I have seen a flock of crows attack a raptor and pull it's feathers, so I don't think a nesting eagle would leave her  eggs unattended with so many crows around. Of course I am reading a lot into what I am seeing, but that is my best surmise of what is going on here at this Bald Eagle Nest right now. In summary: She's hungry, he didn't deliver any food yet, he knows this is what she wants, and she is not going to leave the nest to get it herself.

I spent a lot of time watching this Bald Eagle.  It was sitting in a tree when it took off in what I assumed was an attack on several nearby Mallards.  Instead, it made passes at things I could not see, and twice tried to get something in the water and came up empty each time.  It then made low passes over the marsh, but again I could not see it ever got anything.  It did fly low enough over a Canada Goose to upset the goose, and one of the local Red-tails made a direct attack on it as it tried to land in a tree.

Media notes: Eagle carrying branch to rebuild nest in rain
Observation Details: This long-standing Lake Wildwood eagle nest (fledged young in 2021, 2022, 2023) had been damaged in the Feb. 5 strong windstorm. During another strong wind storm on the night of March 1-2, a structural branch failed and most of the remaining nest came tumbling down. I looked through the sticks and branches scattered on the ground and found no eggs or chicks. (Lots of fish skulls and vertebrae.) Today, in continuing cold (37 F.), wind, rain and hail, the adult pair were very active at the nest. I saw them perched on the nest remnants, chirping at each other. And I saw one of the birds (they could be differentiated, at least today, by the dark stains on one bird's tail) repeatedly fly away to the woods to the east and return with tree branches that it added to the nest remnants. The stained-tail bird flew away for 20 minutes and returned without food or nest material. See photos.

Juvenile flew in around 7 and caused a huge stir. The whole wetlands lit up with alarm calls, from the geese to the herons all screaming loudly as he soared in. Throughout his very short, unsuccessful visit, he was constantly mobbed and dive bombed (even while perched) by blue jays and rwbs. Even the great blue heron got in on the action and was pacing around the wetlands with his wings puffed out, croaking loudly. After a few minutes perched atop a tree, the eagle had enough and fly away, still being pursued by some very angry blackbirds.
